;Open source should continue to be the heart of the Internet, so we can all see, verify, and contribute to its future.
Ri jaqäl b'itz'ib' k'o chi k'a ja ri' ruk'u'x ri K'amaya'l, richin chi qonojel yojtikïr niqatz'ët, niqanik'oj chuqa' niqato' pa ruk'aslem ri chwa'q kab'ij.


;Open source software – technology built with code that is open for view, use, and modification – is the engine that powers a huge amount of the Internet, from servers to operating systems to the bots that fetch your search results. It’s the infrastructure that makes the Web a truly public resource: transparent, trustworthy, and collaborative, so that anyone with an idea can contribute. But much like our IRL infrastructure, we have to commit the attention and resources to maintain it.
Ri rukema' jaqäl b'itz'ib' – na'ob'âl nuk'un rik'in jaqäl b'itz'ib' richin rutz'etik, rokisaxik chuqa' ruk'exik – ja ri' ri k'wayöl ri nitzuqu' richin k'ïy chi re ri K'amaya'l, achi'el taq ruk'u'x samaj chuqa' samajel taq q'inoj ke ri k'a ri taq ch'ich' ala's ri k'o yekïl. Ja ri ch'akulal nib'ano chi ri Ajk'amaya'l nok jun tob'äl kichin winaqi': ch'ajch'öj, kuqel k'u'x chi rij chuqa' to'el richin chi xab'achike winäq rik'in runa'oj tito'on. Junam achi'el ri qach'akulal IRL, k'atzinel niqaya' qatzub'al chuqa' taq qatob'äl pa ruwi' richin tik'ase'.


